answers.body_markdown:
The issue is the implementation of the [`EasyMock#capture(Capture&lt;T&gt;)`][1] method that always returns `null`:

```
public static &lt;T&gt; T capture(final Capture&lt;T&gt; captured) {
    reportMatcher(new Captures&lt;T&gt;(captured));
    return null;
}
```

This would not be a problem if the mocked method would accept an object type `Long` as a parameter:

```
void doSomething(long id);
```
... however, the `long` primitive type is present and the attempt of unboxing the return value (`null`) of the [`EasyMock#capture(Capture&lt;T&gt;)`][1] method fails on `NullPointerException`.

The fix is simple: For this reason, there were introduced method variations suitable for primitive types, such as [`EasyMock#captureLong(Capture&lt;Long&gt;)`][2]:

```
myInterface.doSomething(captureLong(capturedId));
```

  [1]: https://easymock.org/api/org/easymock/EasyMock.html#capture-org.easymock.Capture-
  [2]: https://easymock.org/api/org/easymock/EasyMock.html#captureLong-org.easymock.Capture-

